{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492950","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492950"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:51:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:51:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1190"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1190"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.65,0.29,0,0.01,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97541"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1190","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1190"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1190"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80141"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"38"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5364"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1344"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13208"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16197"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17684"},{"type":"contributions","id":"29967"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38628"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44980"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97541","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97541"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 42-year-old man presents for a routine checkup. His 80-year-old aunt was recently diagnosed with metastatic right colon cancer. He has no other relatives with a known diagnosis of colorectal cancer. He worries that he might be at an increased risk of colon cancer due to his family history and wants to confirm if he has cancer or not. He does not have any gastrointestinal symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance alone","Immunochemical faecal occult blood testing","CT colonography","Low dose aspirin","Colonoscopy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EScreening for colon cancer is carried out with immunochemical faecal occult blood testing (iFOBT) and/or colonoscopy. The screening guidelines depend on the baseline risk of developing colon cancer. Risk stratification based on family history is summarised below:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 1 - similar risk as the general population\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with no family history of colorectal cancer OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne 1st-degree relative with CRC \u226560 years\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: FOBT should be completed every 2 years from 45 years old as per usual screening protocol. Colonoscopy is generally not recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 2 - moderately increased risk\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic people with one 1st-degree relative CRC diagnosed \u0026lt;60 years OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age or one 1st-degree and one or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed at any age\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: Colonoscopy should be offered 5 yearly starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest diagnosis of CRC in a 1st-degree relative, or age \u003Cstrong\u003E50 \u003C/strong\u003E(whichever is earliest). Note that the age threshold for first-degree relatives has recently changed from 55 to 60 years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E\u003Cem\u003ECategory 3 - high risk, excluding hereditary cancer syndromes\u003C/em\u003E\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAsymptomatic with two 1st-degree and one 2nd-degree relative with colorectal cancer, with at least one diagnosed before 50 years old OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETwo 1st-degree relatives and two or more 2nd-degree relatives diagnosed with CRC at any age OR\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThree or more 1st-degree relatives with CRC at any age.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScreening\u003C/strong\u003E: refer to the familial cancer clinic for genetic assessment before a screening decision is made if Lynch syndrome has not been excluded. If Lynch syndrome is excluded, colonoscopy should be offered every 5 years starting at \u003Cstrong\u003E10 years younger\u003C/strong\u003E than the earliest age of diagnosis of colorectal cancer in a first-degree relative or age \u003Cstrong\u003E40 \u003C/strong\u003Eyears (whichever is earliest)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAccording to this risk stratification, the patient is Category 1 or at average risk of colorectal cancer (CRC) as he has only a single second-degree relative diagnosed with CRC. He should be managed according to the screening guidelines according to the Category 1 group and should be screened for CRC with \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmunochemical faecal occult blood testing\u003C/strong\u003E every two years starting at the\u003Cstrong\u003E age of 45 until the age of 74\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETherefore, as this man is aged 42 years, \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance alone\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate. Nonetheless, he could be offered a faecal immunochemical test, provided he is fully informed of the possible harms and benefits of asymptomatic screening.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT colonography\u003C/strong\u003E is indicated in patients who need to undergo colonoscopy but have a contraindication for colonoscopy. This patient does not need a colonoscopy or CT colonography at this moment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELow dose aspirin\u003C/strong\u003E (100mg daily) may be considered for colorectal cancer prevention in consultation with a healthcare professional for people aged 45-70 years who are at higher-than-average risk. However, this patient is both too young and at average risk, making this option inappropriate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFlexible sigmoidoscopy and colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E are indicated in patients who have a positive iFOBT on routine screening or are symptomatic. This patient may need a colonoscopy if his iFOBT is positive but would not be the next step in management in this scenario.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Average risk asymptomatic individuals do not need colorectal cancer screening until the age of 45 years.","Low-dose aspirin may be considered for colorectal cancer prevention in consultation with a healthcare professional."],"references":["RACGP. Guidance for preventative activities in general practice: colorectal cancer. 2024. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/preventive-activities-in-general-practice/cancer/colorectal-cancer","Cancer Council Australia. Clinical practice guidelines for the prevention, early detection and management of colorectal cancer. Available at: https://www.cancer.org.au/clinical-guidelines/colorectal-cancer"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80141"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1190"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80141"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-07T20:47:47+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-11T21:34:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1190"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97541"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"38","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/38"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"em